Pre-heat your #oven{} to 200 degrees. Your first job is to get the croutons in your
oven. Cut the @Ciabatta{1} into 2cm sized chunks. Pop them into a #bowl{} and
sprinkle over half the @Curry Powder Mix{½}. Mix well to ensure the ciabatta
chunks are evenly coated. Pop them on a #baking tray{} and drizzle over @olive
oil{1%tbsp}. Bake for ~{8%mins} and then keep to one side.

Pop the @British Chicken Breasts{2} into the same bowl you used for your
croutons and sprinkle over the remaining curry powder, @Soy Sauce{½%tbsp} and
@oil{½%tbsp}. Mix well to make sure the chicken breasts are nicely coated.

Put a #frying pan{} on high heat and once the pan is hot, cook the chicken
breasts for ~{2%mins} on each side until golden brown. Transfer them to a
baking tray and roast in your oven for ~{12%mins}.

> The chicken is cooked when the centre is no longer pink.

With all the cooking underway, give the bowl you used for the croutons and
chicken a good wash and get on with the salad. Roughly chop the
@Coriander{5}. Chop the tops and bottoms off the @Carrot{2}, peel and then grate
on the coarse side of your #grater{}. Pop the carrots and chopped coriander
into your bowl.

Cut the @Red Onion{¼} in half through the root, peel and then slice into thin
half moon shapes, add this to the bowl with the carrot and coriander.

> Red onion is quite strong when raw so add as much as you see fit. Keep any
> leftovers wrapped in clingfilm and use another time.

Cut the @Radish{1} into quarters. Remove the core from the @Red Pepper{1} and
then slice as thin as you can. Mix the radishes and peppers into the salad.

Next, make the dressing in a #small bowl{}. Juice the @Lime{1}, mix in
@sugar{2%tsp}(if you have some) and the remaining @Soy Sauce{1%tbsp}. Pour this
over the salad and mix well.

When your chicken has finished cooking, allow it to cool for a few mins before
slicing each breast widthways into six pieces. Serve your chicken on top of a
generous pile of your zingy salad and finish with a few crunchy croutons.
Enjoy!